<paragraph blockId="13.[151,1436,1615,1922]" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,263,1855,1881]" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">Note.</emphasis>
This species closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dietrich &amp; Dmitriev" authorityYear="2007" box="[635,768,1856,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Neozygina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="40" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="expanda">
<emphasis box="[635,768,1856,1881]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="40">N. expanda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but has the distal projections of the aedeagus much more slender. The specific name refers to the forcipate aedeagal apex.
</paragraph>
